claims.claim_content:
An onboard system for controlling flight of an unmanned aerial vehicle (10), comprising: a flight management system (40) configured for controlling flight of the unmanned aerial vehicle (10);
a mission control module (2) configured to manage the mission by issuing commands addressed to the flight management system (40) for guiding the unmanned aerial vehicle (10) to perform a mission;
a safety module (8) configured to issue commands addressed to the flight management system (40) for guiding the unmanned aerial vehicle (10) to continue flying safely in a safe mode;
a communication control component (6) which is switchable between a mission state in which the flight management system (40) receives communication of commands from the mission control module (2) and a safety state in which the flight management system (40) receives communication of commands from the safety module (8); and
a monitor module (4) configured to determine whether a trigger condition warranting a change in mode from a mission mode to a safe mode is present or not and to cause the communication control component (6) to switch from the mission state to the safety state when the trigger condition is present.

A method (100) for controlling flight of an unmanned aerial vehicle (10), comprising: (a) sending commands from a mission control module (2) onboard the unmanned aerial vehicle (10) to a flight management system (40) onboard the unmanned aerial vehicle for guiding the unmanned aerial vehicle (10) to perform a mission;
(b) monitoring validity of the commands sent from the mission control module (2) to the flight management system (40) to determine when a trigger condition is present based on whether the commands sent from the mission control module (2) to the flight management system (40) are valid or invalid; and
(c) guiding the unmanned aerial vehicle (10) in accordance with the validated commands sent from the mission control module (2) to the flight management system (40).

The method as recited in claim 13, further comprising: (d) determining that a command sent from the mission control module (2) to the flight management system (40) is invalid;
(e) discontinuing the communication of commands from the mission control module (2) to the flight management system (40);
(f) communicating commands from a safety module (8) onboard the unmanned aerial vehicle (10) to the flight management system (40) for guiding the unmanned aerial vehicle (10) to operate in a safe mode; and
rebooting the mission control module (2) when the command issued by the mission control module (2) is invalid.

A method for bistatic radar target detection comprising: launching a UAV (14) and navigating the UAV (14) with a ramjet engine (30) at supersonic cruise to beyond a radar range limit;
maintaining a mothership aircraft (10) on a flight profile outside the radar range limit;
extending antenna arms (22) to act as air brakes reducing speed and providing boresight orientation of Tx/Rx modules (34) for bistatic RF pulse reception;
employing a high power radar system (40) on the mothership aircraft (10) to emit radar pulses;
employing receive (Rx) modules (34) on the UAV (14) as a bistatic receiver to receive reflected radar pulses from targets (20); and,
transmitting target data from the UAV (14) via a communications data link (50) to the mothership aircraft (10).

A method compreceiving (600), by a computer system (224) located onboard an unmanned aerial vehicle (202), sensor data (228);
processing (602), by the computer system (224), the sensor data (228) to generate information of interest (230) related to at least one target, while the unmanned aerial vehicle (202) is outside a communications range (218) of a control station (210); and
identifying, by the computer system (224), a number of actions (225) to be performed based on the information of interest (230) related to the at least one target, while the unmanned aerial vehicle (202) is outside the communications range (218) of the control station (210).

The method of claim 1, further comprising: identifying, by a computer system (224) located onboard the unmanned aerial vehicle (202), information related to at least one target, wherein the information is based on data that is received from at least one of a sensor system, a target detector, a target tracker, or a number of vehicle systems (306) implemented onboard the unmanned aerial vehicle (202);
evaluating, by the computer system (224) autonomously, the operation of the unmanned aerial vehicle (202) and a performance of a mission of the unmanned aerial vehicle (202) using the information, while the unmanned aerial vehicle (202) is outside a communications range (218) of a control station (210); and
identifying, by the computer system (224) autonomously, a number of actions (225) to be performed based on evaluation of the operation of and the performance of the mission of the unmanned aerial vehicle (202), while the unmanned aerial vehicle (202) is outside the communications range (218) of the control station (210).

A system (20) for autonomously tracking a target from an air vehicle, the system comprising: an automatic target recognition (ATR) module (22) configured to receive video information, process the video information, and produce ATR information including target information;
a multi-sensor integrator (MSI) module (24) configured to receive the ATR information, an air vehicle state input and a target state input, process the inputs and produce track information for the target;
a target module (36) configured to receive the track information, process the track information, and produce predicted future state target information;
an ownship module (38) configured to receive the track information, process the track information, and produce predicted future state air vehicle information; and
a planner module (42) configured to receive the predicted future state target information and the predicted future state air vehicle information and generate travel path information including flight and camera steering commands for the air vehicle.

The system of Claim 1, further comprising at least one of a command module (54) configured to analyze an anticipated path of travel for the air vehicle and determine whether the path crosses into any restricted airspace or intersects any obstructions;
an automatic target recognition trainer module (62) configured to catalog information about the target;
a self calibration planner module (106) configured to calibrate navigational sensors aboard the air vehicle;
a configuration manager module (108) configured to save a data configuration within the system so that the data configuration can be used in the future;
a legs module (46) configured to predict a flight path for the air vehicle; and
a record/playback module (112) configured to record data associated with a tracking operation.

A method of autonomously tracking a target from an airborne vehicle, the method comprising the steps of: receiving video information input to an automatic target recognition (ATR) module (22), processing the video information, and producing ATR information;
receiving the ATR information, air vehicle state information and target state information as inputs to a multi-sensor integrator (MSI) (24), processing the inputs and producing track information;
receiving the track information as an input to a target module (36), processing the track information, predicting a future state of the target and producing target information;
receiving the track information as an input to an ownship module (38), processing the track information, predicting a future state of the air vehicle and producing ownship information; and
receiving the target information and the ownship information as inputs to a planner module (42) and generating a travel path for the air vehicle.

The method of Claim 12, further comprising at least one of generating a weave plan (66) for the air vehicle, the weave plan (66) being designed to maintain a desired distance between the air vehicle and the target while the target is moving and while maintaining the air vehicle within boundaries;
generating a loiter plan for the air vehicle, the loiter plan being designed to maintain a desired distance between the air vehicle and the target while the target is stationary;
generating a region search plan for the air vehicle, the region search plan being designed to allow the air vehicle to scan an area;
analyzing an anticipated path of travel for the air vehicle and determining whether the path crosses into any restricted airspace or intersects any obstructions.
cataloging information about the target;
calibrating navigational sensors aboard the air vehicle;
predicting a flight path for the air vehicle; and
recording data associated with a tracking operation.
